                              APPENDIX A

             EXAMPLE PROGRAM TO INTERROGATE AN EPHEMERIS



The program JPLPLEPH (the Fortran source and the executable image are
in JPLDIR) demonstrates the use of the PLEPH routine.  Once compiled,
and linked with JPLDIR:JPL/L, it can be run as follows:

     1.  $ ASSIGN/USER JPLDIR:DE200.DAT FOR012

     2.  $ RUN JPLDIR:JPLPLEPH

JPLPLEPH calls the PLEPH subroutine (which in turn calls the XCONST
and XSTATE subroutines) to interpolate from the ephemeris file on
Fortran unit 12 the heliocentric position and velocity of the Earth
for the instant of dynamical time TDB = 2440000.5.  The output is as
follows:

 -0.4546344405877503     -0.8303581726592454     -0.3600779865854318
  1.5096053509658230E-02 -7.1486193233325490E-03
-3.1004921587923199E-03

The Fortran source of JPLPLEPH follows.



















                                - 10 -
EXAMPLE PROGRAM TO INTERROGATE AN EPHEMERIS                   Page A-2


      PROGRAM JPLPLEPH

*+
*
*  - - - - - - - - -
*   J P L P L E P H
*  - - - - - - - - -
*
*  Example program using Starlink subroutine PLEPH to interpolate a
*  JPL planetary ephemeris.  The heliocentric Earth position
*  and velocity for a given instant of TDB are determined.
*
*  Input is from the disc form of the JPL ephemeris (as output
*  by JPLREAD66 or JPLSHORT) on I/O unit 12.
*
*
*  P.T.Wallace   Starlink   December 1985
*
*+

      IMPLICIT NONE

*  PLEPH arguments
      DOUBLE PRECISION TDB
      INTEGER NP,NC
      DOUBLE PRECISION PV(6)



*  TDB = Julian Date 2440000.5
      TDB=40000D0
*  Body is the Earth
      NP=3
*  Origin is the Sun
      NC=11

*  Read and interpolate the ephemeris
      CALL PLEPH(TDB,NP,NC,PV)

*  List the resulting position and velocity
      PRINT *,PV

      END










